bio:
Chi siamo:
MADlab è una piccola officina dotata di una serie di strumenti computerizzati in grado di realizzare un’ampia gamma di oggetti.

Questo nuovo spazio all’interno del Sestiere della Maddalena, grazie alla dotazione di scanner, stampanti 3D e altri strumenti tecnologici, vuole essere un luogo pronto ad offrire servizi personalizzati di fabbricazione digitale e momenti di formazione dedicati a creativi, insegnanti, studenti e curiosi.

Un luogo dove avvicinarsi alle nuove tecnologie ed entrare a far parte del mondo dei makers!

Il progetto MADlab è realizzato dalla Cooperativa Sociale Il Laboratorio in collaborazione con Scuola di Robotica e Associazione Festival della Scienza con il sostegno del Comune di Genova nell’ambito delle iniziative del Patto per lo sviluppo per la Maddalena e il contributo della Compagnia di San Paolo tramite il Bando Pubblico Un passo avanti.

Mission:
Il progetto MADlab intende sviluppare e insediare all'interno del Sestiere della Maddalena uno spazio condiviso aperto agli abitanti del quartiere e a disposizione di tutta la città.
Uno spazio che, prendendo ispirazione dal nuovo fenomeno dei Fablab, permetta a tutti quelli che lo frequentano di utilizzare ed imparare ad utilizzare nuovi strumenti teconologici come scanner e stampanti 3D.
Il fine ultimo è quello di creare una comunità di "makers"composta da insegnati studenti e cittadini che trova all'interno del sestiere un luogo dove poter sviluppare e produrre i propri progetti

This is Me =)

I am a 18-year-old student living in the Netherlands. In 2014 my school offered me a rare course: together with another student and a teacher we could follow a two-day-course at the Windesheim University in Zwolle. At that course we were able to build and program a RepRap Prusa i3 3D printer. The idea was that we could pass on our knowledge about the subject of 3D printing to other students. Our vision is also to be able to use 3D printing as a tool for projects where students can send us models they have made and we can print it.
Together with the two people with whom I followed the 3D printing course we try to perfect our skills in 3D printing by printing things from Thingiverse. Thingiverse is an amazing website for us because of the amount and variety of models available to print.
We now use a Builder Dual-Feed 3D printer to print our models.

bio:
I'm a mechanical engineer. I like bicycles a lot, so a lot of my designs are cycling products. I enjoy reverse-engineering commercial products, adding features, & fabricating them via machining/3D printing.

I believe in liberating certain products because they're common & well-suited for 3D printing. I hate spending money & like CADing, so it's reasonable to make these things. I upload all the things I've made that will almost certainly not make me money, or commercial inspirations are widely available.

All my designs include the relevant design files should you want to modify/customize them. Please give me credit if you do this. If I forget to include these files, please let me know. I also may add other features/modify the designs at any time. Contact me if you have any ideas. I'll do it if there's a decent amount of interest, or it's a very good idea. For commercial spinoffs, I only do them if I have the actual part (if it's a fairly complex geometry, etc.). Only if the geometry is relatively simple do I base the model off of good pictures found online.

I can use Solidworks, Inventor, & Creo, though the former is my favorite.

I have used:

  • Pronterface
  • Slic3r
  • Cura
  • Makerware
  • MakerBot Replicator
  • Lulzbot Mini
  • some other MakerBot
  • HIPS, PLA, ABS

Designing stuff:

A lot of my designs involve metric bicycle hardware, which are fairly small. Since the vast majority of my designs are meant to be 3D printed, I resize everything to account for strength loss & shrinkage. My best rule of thumb for holes and nut insets around 5 mm in diameter is to apply a 115% scaling factor. I arrived at this just through trial-&-error, but it seems to work very well. If you are rendering these designs in metal, I suggest you redesign from the ground up, since you'll be leaving a lot of redundant material, & it'll weigh unnecessarily more.

Common bike industry threads: http://www.parktool.com/blog/repair-help/basic-thread-concepts#article-section-6

Zipties: I ususally specify this, but I like using 0.20" wide zip ties.

Cable stops & housing

  • shift ferrules: 12.77 mm long, 5.78 mm OD, 1.80 mm cable hole, 4.28 mm ID
  • Shimano shift barrel adjuster: 7.99 mm ferrule seat depth, 5.94 mm ID, 12.40 mm threaded length, 4.86 mm total outside thread diameter, 2.24 mm cable hole, 12 mm length
  • brake barrel adjuster: 7.98 mm ferrule seat depth, 6.41 mm ID, 8.69 OD (variable), 10.31 mm barrel length, 14.45 mm threaded length (with locknut on), 2.45 mm cable hole

Cable housing

  • 4.17 mm shift cable housing OD
  • 4.95 mm brake cable housing OD

1985 road bike tubing

  • 28.85 mm downtube
  • 25.56 mm top tube
  • 29.01 mm seat tube
  • 27.81 mm generic tube (average of three above)

General safety disclaimer: use my designs at your own risk.

Other warnings: some of my designs date back several months. I try to be accurate in my descriptions, especially when it comes to features, hardware, & installation, but I'm too lazy to go back & verify some of these things, or I just remember incorrectly. So be aware of that. If you find an error, let me know.

Unless I explicitly said I tested a design, assume that I didn't. In that case, don't expect things to work if I didn't test them first.

I took it upon myself to fix my speaker but then it expanded from there. I also had my headlamp fall and break rendering my ability to see and be seen at night useless. The speaker had a light that had also broken but the motherboard to the speaker still had a spot for the light. It also had hook-ups for a battery and controls for the sound system. With my soldering station and 3D printers, why couldn't I make an entire system? It may take me a little why. I procrastinate sometimes. but I hope to have it done before summer of 2018 is over.

bio: Big feet

I always wanted to be an inventor, but I ended up becoming a machinist. I made military parts for a bit, but it wasn't as glorious as I thought it'd be. So I ended up working for a steel company that heavily relied on Water Jet and Laser tech. My CNC experience accumulated over time, but I was never free to make anything for myself.

Now that changed when I got a Cupcake CNC Ultra.

Im studying electrical engineering and bought my 3D printer mainly just to print enclosures for my projects. As you see on my thingy-things, my design skills are below novice. since i dont care about aesthetics, my things just have to have a practical use.

bio: I'm a quadcopter enthusiast!
Mechanical Engineer
I like 3D stuff

At heart and by training I am a mechanical engineer. I am fascinated by things that move and do stuff. For this reason I play around with making all kinds of mechanical constructions for amusement. I have a metal lathe, and metal working tools for repurposing old electric hardware. 3D printing is the ideal method of realising parts that I cannot find a suitable bit for in the pile of electrical equipment that I use for parts, and would be near impossible to manufacture using traditional tools. My website http://www.techmonkeybusiness.com has more about my projects and activities.

Well actually, the printer I use is not my own, but rather bought by my partner for her projects. I'm a bit worried that I am commandeering it for my projects. I'll just have to be nice to her to make up for it.

A word of warning: I am not a purist. My designs are very likely to include other materials and probably use tools other than a printer.

It's all fun.
I like Pokemon!
